The ecosystem map — what library does what.

A short map so you can recognize names when they come up.

For hypertext transfer protocol clients — the standard library has u-r-l-lib dot request; the most-reached-for third party is requests for synchronous code or h-t-t-p-x for sync plus async. For h-t-t-p servers — the standard library has h-t-t-p dot server; third-party defaults are fast-a-p-i, flask, or starlette. For tabular data — the standard library has c-s-v and s-q-lite three; third-party defaults are pandas and polars. For numeric data — the standard library has array; third-party defaults are num-py and sci-py. For machine learning — no standard-library entry; defaults are scikit-learn, py-torch, or tensor-flow. For plotting — matplotlib, plotly, seaborn.

For j-s-o-n, the stdlib json module is enough. For y-a-m-l, p-y-y-a-m-l or rumel-y-a-m-l. For reading t-o-m-l, the stdlib toml-lib since three point eleven. For writing t-o-m-l, the third-party tomli dash w.

For testing, the stdlib unittest works but py-test from notebook ten is dominant. For type checking, my-py, py-right, or ruff. For linting and formatting, ruff and black. For async, the stdlib asyncio plus trio or any-io. For command-line interfaces, the stdlib arg-parse, or third-party click or typer. For date and time, the stdlib date-time plus zone-info, or third-party pendulum or arrow. For templating, the stdlib string dot template, or jinja two.

You will install only the ones your project needs. The list is here so the names are not a surprise.
